<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>CROPPROTECTION ASSOCIATION RESPONSE TO THE EFRA COMMITTEE INQUIRY ON FOOD SECURITY</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">WRITTEN EVIDENCE FROM CROP PROTECTION ASSOCIATION</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Crop Protection Association (CPA) welcomes the opportunity to respond to the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Committee inquiry into Food Security.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The CPA is a key</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> voice of the UK Plant Science Industry</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, promoting</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the role of modern plant science in safeguarding our food supply from seed to shelf. The Association represents companies in the UK engaged in the development and manufacture of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a range of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> plant science te</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">chnologies including </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">crop</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> protection prod</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ucts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, or pesticides</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. We have 2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> member companies, covering around 95% of the UK pesticide market. A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> full list of Members can be found at: </span><a href="http://www.cropprotection.org.uk/members.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.croppro</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">tection.org.uk/members.aspx</span></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The debate around food security in the UK, Europe and across the globe has been well-rehearsed over recent years, and we do not intend, in this submission, to dwell on the arguments and evidence demonstrating that global demand for food will continue to in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">crease in the coming decades. Suffice to say that the CPA </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recognis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">es that there are a number of issues </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to be addressed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> if supply is to meet this growing demand, including a reduction in food waste, a change in consumer habits, and a focus on a sustainable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">increase in production. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As the UK voice of the crop protection industry, this submission will focus on the last of these, increasing production in a sustainable way. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Used in this context, crop protection is about the effective management of pests, diseas</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">es and weeds</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to protect and enhance crop yields</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and is primarily achieved through the application of chemical controls, or pesticides, which include insecticides, fungicides and herbicides.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The role of crop protection products in achieving food security</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The CPA believes that, even with improvements in reducing food waste, and assuming some changes to consumer diets that favour more sustainable production models (something that may be hard to achieve in practice), agricultural production will need to incr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ease its global output in future</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he challenge of increasing production</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> while minimising the environment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">al</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">impact </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in doing so, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">will be the crucial element in achieving</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> adequate</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> global food security. As the Governmen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Foresight Report on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Global Food and Farming Futures </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">stated, “…there is wide agreement that feeding the global population in 2050 will require the continued achievement of historical agricultural growth rates. Given limitations in land available for crops in the future, such g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rowth must be largely based on increase</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s in yields.” </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The same report notes that in 2009, the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Food and Agriculture Organisation of the UN</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">FAO</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> estimated that to meet global demand, food production would have to increase by 70% in the period 2000–2050</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">How</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ever, it is widely acknowledged that in much of the developed world, including the UK and Europe, increases in average yields of major food crops are not being maintained, and while major advances in crop productivity were witnessed for many years after th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e Second World War, there has in general been very little improvement in yields over the last two decades. For instance, analysis by the Home Grown Cereals Authority shows that the period from the 1940s to the 1990s saw national average yields rising from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.7 t/ha to 7.6 t/ha. Since then farm wheat yields have stalled, varying between 7.0 and 8.0 t/ha but with no rising trend.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The reasons for these yield plateaus are not </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">well</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> understood, but it is clear that unless yield increases can be kick-started farmer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s will struggle to keep up with increased global demand for food. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Crop protection products form a key part of a farmer’s armoury</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The ability to effectively control insect, disease and weed pressures throughout the year </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> crucial to maintaining or improving yields.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">CPA research has shown</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that without protection, farmers would lose on average more than 40% of crop yield pre-harvest and a further 10% post-harvest.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, a meta-analysis from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">McGill </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">University</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Mont</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">real, comparing organic yields with those in conventional systems across a range of crops</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> found that, while yield differences depend on system and site characteristics, averages range from 5% lower organic yields for rain-fed legumes and perennials on wea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">k-acidic to weak-alkaline soils to 34% lower yields when the conventional and organic systems are most comparable. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is important to note that according to a recent </span><a href="http://hffa.info/files/hffa-wp-3-2013.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Humboldt study</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> even a 5% reduc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in EU agriculture</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> result in a deficit in food production for some 50 million people, a deficit that would have to be made up by extra production in countries outside of the EU. A 34% reduction would therefore likely be catastrophic. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It should be noted that the CPA recognises </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">organic farmin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g can play an important role</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> providing evidence of the effectiveness of a range of techniques in controlling pests. Nevertheless, it is clear that managing pests with pesticides is an important el</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ement in protecting crop yields, and hence in enabling farmers to meet demand for food.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The best approach to effective pest management combine</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> chemical an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d non-chemical control methods, often referred to as integrated pest management.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Pesticides and sustainable production</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">esticides are amongst the most heavily-regulated products in Europe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and it currently takes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> around</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a decade, costing over £150m, to bring an active ingredient to market. A large proportion of this time and cost is dedicated to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">research required under </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the regulatory system to achieve registration. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This regulatory process, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">involving rigorous scrutiny by independent scientific experts, ensures plant protection products are safe for consumers, for the people who use them and for the environment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, the Voluntary Initiative, the industry-led scheme of which the CPA </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is a key member, ensures that pesticides are used responsibly out in the field. This includes training for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">farmers,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> through continuous professional development</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">so that they use pesticides safely, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">testing of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> equipment used for applying pesticides </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to ensure it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is fit for purpose.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Pesticides </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are, therefore, an integral</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> part of a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">modern, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">productive farming system </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">aims to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">minimis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> pest damage and improv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> yields, while contributing to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sustainable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">system</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that protects the environment. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">By focusin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g on approaches that aim to maximise yields on a given area of land, c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">onventional agriculture optimises both the productivity of cultivated land and the availability of non-cultivated land for other purposes. This includes land used for conservation and wi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ldlife benefits, such as un-cropped headlands and field corners, often managed under current agri-environment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">schemes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">under</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the CAP. Lower-yield agriculture, for instance under </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">low-input or organic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> systems, would inevitably put pressure on bringing currently un-cropped land back into production if yield levels are to be maintained or increased, with clear consequences for wildlife and the environment.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, direct application of pesticides o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n land set aside for conservation can help ensure that land is properly managed to provide maximum benefit. Some of the best examples of conservation farming in the UK take a conventional approach, both to growing crops and to managing land for biodiversit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y and the environment. This approach often sees environmental measures considered a crop like any other – managed with the same time, effort and expense, and under the same agronomic principles as the rest of the farm. This may, for example, mean headlands</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> cultivated to produce a strip of pollen-rich flowers are treated with herbicides to manage weeds, so producing a habitat more attractive to pollinators and other beneficial invertebrates. Not only does this have a widespread positive impact on wildlife, b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ut the presence of beneficial</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> insect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s on field margins provides additional pest control in neighbouring crops, reducing the need to apply insecticides later in the year.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The political landscape for technological responses to the food security challenge</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t is clear, through practices such as this, that pesticides are part of the solution and not the problem with regard to sustainable production</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and food security</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, European policy makers have increasingly taken a policy approach that restricts the a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vailability of technological solutions to increasing food production. Recent developments in pesticides policy are a case in point.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The recent moratorium on using neonicotioid insecticides, in response to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> theoretical</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> concerns about the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> potential</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> sub-letha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l effects of these products on pollinators, showed a worrying disregard for the regulatory system which had app</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">roved the products, and apparently ignored the damaging impact on crop yields and pollinator habitats that such a move will bring about. The deci</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sion is currently subject to legal challenges in Europe by CPA members. There are further changes to the regulatory system in Europe currently underway which will likely result in fewer crop protection products b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eing made available to farmers, with very re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">al implications for agricultural production across the continent.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This not only hampers farmers’ ability to produce food, and certainly hinders attempts to break out of current crop yield plateaus, but also puts increasing pressures on remaining products </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to control pests. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Put simply, fewer products being used increases the tendency for weeds, diseases and insects to develop resistance, exacerbating the problem.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, there</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">appears to be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a general approach</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in Europe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that equates pesticides with environmental harm. This approach seeks to prohibit pesticide use from schemes and areas which are intended to benefit wildlife or the environment, for instance Environmental Focus Areas under the new Pillar 1 of the recently </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reformed CAP. Such an approach ignores the fact that pesticides can be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> used in providing wildlife-friendly habitats, and sends a misleading and simplistic message that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the use</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">esticides is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">incompatible with sustainable production.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Quite simpl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y, the reverse is just as likely to be true; without the use of pesticides, the tradeoff between food production and wildlife promotion would become increasingly stark.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It should be noted that the UK government in recent years has taken a far more </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rational and balanced approach to these issues, recognising the vital role crop protection products</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> play in farming, as well as other technologies which might assist productivity such as GMOs.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> However, it is crucial that the UK government, whatever its pol</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">itical make-up, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">maintains a science-based, rational and balanced approach, and vigorously promotes the same with other EU member states and institutions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">impact</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of Europe’s obstructive approach to modern farming methods can be seen in recent research </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">into R&amp;D investment on crop protection in Europe. Conducted by consultants Phillips McDougall, it showed that the share of crop protection R&amp;D investment attributable to products being developed for the European </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">market, as a proportion of global investment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> has fallen from 33.3% in the 1980s to 7.7% in the 2005-14 period. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The upshot is that European farmers have far less new technology to drive agricultural production than their competitors in other regions of the world.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This is particularly important as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not only does Europe have one of the highest levels of potential agricultural productivity in the world, but climate change projections show that it will become even more favourable for production compared to most other regions over the next 50 years.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Despite this obvious justification for Europe playing a leading role in supporting agricultural productivity to feed a growing global population, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">current </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">European policy seem</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> instead content for European farming to stagnate, instead hoping to rely on the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rest of the world to provide its own food as well as Europe’s. At a time when many developing countries struggle to manage their own food security, and with climate change only likely to exacerbate those struggles, this appears to be an alarmingly short-si</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ghted and conceited approach.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It also carries with it the very real risk that, even if policy makers wish in future to stimulate an increase in European production, the technology, techniques and resources simply won’t be available to do so.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">CPA</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recog</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nises that in order to ensure adequate future supply of food across the globe a wide range of issues need to be addressed, including food waste, consumer diets and barriers to trade</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Nevertheless, increases</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in production form a crucial element in respondin</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">g to this challenge</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, and it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> vital, if we are to bolster our resilience to demand increases, that we provide the right incentives </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">within a constructive policy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">environment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to enable farmers to produce more.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">EU policy makers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">must retain an open-mind to the potential for technology to support this aim. The CPA would like European policy-makers to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">foster</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> conditions and a business environment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that incentivise investment in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> research and development (R&amp;D). To make this happen, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">EU must promote a better integration of science and policy-making</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, moving</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> away</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from hazard-based legislation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and instead favour policy based on robust science and a risk-benefit approach. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This should mean (1) a formal role for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Commission’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Chief Sci</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">entific Adviser (CSA) for the EU institutions to review the use of scientific evidence in risk management legislation, regulation or administrative decisions, and require further scientific assessment where appropriate; (2) Supporting the EU CSA with a net</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">work of  Scientific Advisers in all Commission Services and in all Member States; (3) Creating a more inclusive model for scientific assessment that relies on full use of scientific evidence and expertise in risk evaluation and decision-making, including i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nput from academia, the public and the private sector (industry scientists); (4) Enhancing public understanding of science through improved education and communication.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We also believe there should be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> common</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> institutional understanding of the Precaution</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Principle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, thereby enabling decision-makers to better balance the benefits, risks and uncertainties of policy decisions. Considering precaution in a broader framework with proportionality and innovation will provide a basis for balanced decision-making</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Policy-makers should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">make better use of impact assessments to understand</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the potential impact of their political, legislative and regulatory decisions in social, economic and environmental terms, including innovation. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mpact assessment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> should be carrie</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d out independently in a participatory and transparent way to better inform decision-makers for all policy and legislative initiatives.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Finally, the EU would benefit from a regulatory fitness check for the Crop Protection Sector, carried out by examining </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the ever-increasing regulatory burdens for their practicability, efficiency, and impact on innovation, and taking into account both primary and secondary legislation and their interaction. The lessons learned should form the basis of a proportional, effici</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ent, cost-effective and innovation-friendly regulatory framework.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">December 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>